WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.400
Hello everyone, thanks for having me today. It's a real honour to be able to speak to

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:15.960
you all. My name's John Burn-Murdoch. I'm going to be talking for the next 40 minutes

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:21.959
or so about the lessons that I've learned from visualising the COVID-19 pandemic over,

00:00:21.959 --> 00:00:29.080
well, I guess it's now about 12 months. So to set the scene, what I want to do is start

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:34.080
off by talking about the perspective I'm coming from in this talk. So data visualisation

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:40.439
is obviously an enormously broad church. There's all sorts of different uses for database in

00:00:40.439 --> 00:00:45.759
different settings. But what I'm talking about today specifically is data visualisation for

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:52.320
a mass audience. Now, as a visual journalist, I'm always dealing with a large audience to

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:56.840
some extent. The Financial Times is behind a paywall, so it's perhaps not the largest

00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:02.360
audience of all. But what's really changed dramatically over the last year working on

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:07.639
the pandemic is that that audience has become enormous. It's become truly global. It was

00:01:07.639 --> 00:01:14.519
quite obvious from as early as the sort of first couple of weeks of March 2020, that

00:01:14.519 --> 00:01:19.760
I was suddenly, my charts were suddenly being seen by an audience of millions across the

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:24.279
world instead of just the tens of thousands or hundreds of thousands who would typically

00:01:24.279 --> 00:01:29.639
see them on the Financial Times website. So the principles I'm going to be talking

00:01:29.639 --> 00:01:36.720
about today and the best practices are all geared towards communicating to a hugely diverse

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:41.480
audience of people in terms of their familiarity with charts. I'm not saying that what I recommend

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:45.720
today is going to be the case if you're producing a visual installation for an art gallery or

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:51.239
a sort of coffee table style piece of work. But really just thinking about data visualisation

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:58.760
fundamentally is an act of communication and particularly of mass communication. So

00:01:58.760 --> 00:02:03.879
to start with something that I suspect reads as incredibly obvious, but I think is actually

00:02:03.879 --> 00:02:09.080
relatively little discussed in the database world. I'm going to talk about the fact that

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:14.320
to create really effective, really powerful charts, you really need to understand how

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:20.479
people consume charts. Now to sort of talk a little bit about why that's not as obvious

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:26.199
as you might think, if you look online at the numbers of tutorials there are for making

00:02:26.199 --> 00:02:31.279
graphics, making data bits, whether it's in R, Python, D3, you name it, generally they're

00:02:31.279 --> 00:02:39.080
focused on the technical element of constructing a chart. What chart type to choose, how to

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:44.320
get your geometries, your shape, space and colour exactly right, how to do things more

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:51.320
efficiently, optimising interactivity, that kind of thing. There's relatively little on

00:02:51.320 --> 00:03:01.479
thinking about what more qualitative elements you can optimise to ensure that people understand,

00:03:01.479 --> 00:03:10.080
enjoy and remember your charts. This is where I perhaps get almost a bit too corporate or

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:15.559
business focused in my view of this, but when you're making charts for a mass audience,

00:03:15.559 --> 00:03:20.559
it serves you well I think to think about them almost as if you're creating an advert.

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:26.520
There is decades of research from people who create billboard ads for example on what you

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:32.679
should do in terms of messaging, in terms of how you use text, in terms of how you use

00:03:32.679 --> 00:03:39.440
colour and all of that to elicit a specific response in your audience. I think it's that

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:44.960
communication way of thinking that is relatively underrepresented at the moment in best practice

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:51.199
guidelines for charts. So as I say, when I've been creating charts that I'm hoping and latterly

00:03:51.199 --> 00:03:55.839
expecting are going to be seen by an audience of millions, I've really had to focus on first

00:03:55.839 --> 00:04:01.279
of all how do I ensure they're clear enough to reach and be easily understood by millions

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:05.720
of people and then how do I make sure that they stick in their memory and they're not

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:15.639
just post 79 out of 100 that ping on their Twitter feed every day. So without any further

00:04:15.639 --> 00:04:20.000
ado and I think quite fittingly given that I'm talking about lessons I learned from the

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.559
pandemic, it's time to look at the science. So I'm going to show you here some work that

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:31.000
is not my own work, but it's probably the single most influential data viz research

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.359
paper that I've ever come across and it's one that I and our wider team at the FT use

00:04:36.359 --> 00:04:41.200
very frequently and constantly have in our mind when we're thinking about how to optimise

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:46.559
our work for understanding by a mass audience. And that is this paper from a team led by

00:04:46.559 --> 00:04:53.239
Michelle Borkin in the US on what it is, what are the characteristics of visualisations

00:04:53.239 --> 00:04:59.079
that lead people to recognise the story of that graphic and then to recall it later on.

00:04:59.079 --> 00:05:05.559
So the slide I'm going to show you in a second is looking at an eye tracking experiment from

00:05:05.559 --> 00:05:09.359
this paper and I'm going to show you a GIF so it's going to loop if you don't see it

00:05:09.359 --> 00:05:13.640
first time that's fine it'll come again. But what it is is it's showing where people's

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:19.440
eyes actually focus when they're given a chart for a relatively short period of time, 10

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:24.760
seconds, 30 seconds or so and asked what do you see here, what can you make out, what's

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:30.760
the main takeaway. And so what you're going to see is a sort of simple illustration of

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:35.000
a chart and then a blue dot on that chart showing where people look when they're presented

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:42.920
with that chart. And what you see is that blue dot moves straight up to the title of

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:47.239
the chart, has a little explore of the title, then comes down and reads off the axis label

00:05:47.239 --> 00:05:52.040
to see what units the chart is showing and then reads across the chart content itself.

00:05:52.119 --> 00:05:57.799
I'll just let that play again so the eyes go to the title, they then come down to see

00:05:57.799 --> 00:06:03.720
the vertical axis and then they read across the contents of the chart. The key point here

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:09.880
is that that initial focus goes straight to the title and the researchers did additional

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:14.279
follow-up analysis of the same group of participants and found that when people later on were asked

00:06:14.279 --> 00:06:19.679
to remember any information about a chart and just write a sort of free-form description

00:06:19.679 --> 00:06:26.559
of what they'd seen, words featured very prominently. The title, any annotations, labelling

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:31.920
were all mentioned far more often when people remember the chart than the actual visual

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:38.799
content of the plot itself. And that is something we really sort of centre on in our work at the

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:46.959
FT. Our view is very much that you can make a stunning chart, you can have all your geometry

00:06:46.959 --> 00:06:53.279
right, it can be technically executed perfectly but if the messaging, if the text is absent in

00:06:53.279 --> 00:06:58.640
the worst case scenario or too sterile, too dry, you're going to lose a hell of a lot of people.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:04.720
And the way I like to think about that is that your text can help your chart be

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:11.200
understandable, enjoyable and memorable for someone who is quote-unquote not a chart person.

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:17.279
Those of us watching or participating in the conference today I'm sure

00:07:17.279 --> 00:07:22.480
consider ourselves chart people or data people to a greater or lesser extent and that means

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:26.799
when we see a chart it's already a thing that we're familiar with and that we like and that we

00:07:26.799 --> 00:07:31.920
have a sort of way of understanding, whereas there are millions and millions and millions of people

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:37.519
out there, a lot more non-chart people than chart people as it were, who need that helping hand.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:42.720
So to give you an example from the pandemic of this sort of way of thinking in action I'm going

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:49.279
to talk through the origin story as it were of our coronavirus trajectory tracker, so probably

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:55.119
the most high profile chart that we've put out over the last 12 months. And I'm going to start

00:07:55.119 --> 00:08:00.320
by showing how this was sparked, how this came about, by showing you an email I got from one of

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:06.799
my colleagues on I think this was March the 10th or 11th and so she's one of our general news

00:08:06.799 --> 00:08:13.200
reporters who was covering the sort of nascent pandemic back then, or certainly the nascent

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:18.640
epidemic as far as the UK and Europe was concerned. And she just asked me, she's wondering if I had

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:24.320
any data on daily cases in Italy, which of course at the time was sort of the focus of all the

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:27.600
world's attention, there were grim pictures coming out of there in the news reports of

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:33.599
bodies in morgues and that kind of thing. And she's asking me okay do we have any data on

00:08:33.599 --> 00:08:37.919
daily cases for Italy and can we compare that to the UK, perhaps other countries as well.

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:43.919
She hadn't managed to find that data anywhere else. And so I rustled up that same afternoon

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:51.919
or evening or whatever it was, a quick version, sort of version 0.0 as it were of what became our

00:08:52.479 --> 00:08:58.400
high profile trajectory trackers. So you can see for those of you who remember the final version

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:03.280
of this chart or who've encountered the final version of this chart, the geometry, what is shown,

00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:07.919
what is plotted here is essentially unchanged from the final version. We've got the number of

00:09:07.919 --> 00:09:12.960
days since a country first reached its 100th confirmed case going horizontally, and then

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:19.119
you've got a log scale, a logarithmic y-axis of the total number, cumulative number of confirmed

00:09:19.119 --> 00:09:25.440
cases up to that point. And a set of countries shown on there coloured by things like their

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:30.000
global region or other aspects that I'll come on to in a minute. But obviously, you know,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:35.440
if I published that, I doubt it would have cut through to a huge audience the way it ultimately

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:39.679
did. There's nothing here really telling you what's going on. There's a lot of assumed knowledge.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:44.000
Obviously, I sent that to my colleague in the context of this email chain. We both knew what

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.599
we were talking about and looking at. But if I just put this, if we publish this on the FT,

00:09:49.599 --> 00:09:55.599
on social media, you know, a few people, again, chart people or COVID data people would have

00:09:55.599 --> 00:10:02.960
thought, oh, right, interesting. But it wouldn't have had any sort of mass resonance. So here's the

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:09.520
next version of this when it's been styled as we style all our charts on the Financial Times. So

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:16.000
we've got that trademark sort of salmon pink background. I'm now using the colours from our

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:21.440
main colour palette, again, doing some sort of semantic use of colour there. So I'm highlighting

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:26.239
some Asian countries in this sort of light blue. I've got South Korea in a different blue because

00:10:26.239 --> 00:10:30.799
it wasn't clear what trajectory it was on by that point, and a few other colours dotted around.

00:10:30.799 --> 00:10:37.200
There's a bit more text on the chart now. We've got both axes labelled. I've got that source and

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:42.960
footnote at the bottom as well. But again, sure, this, in terms of aesthetics, in terms of design,

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:48.880
this is now neater. This is a better fit for what we would publish on the FT. But it's still missing

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:54.000
those crucial ingredients. So here's the final version that was published. I think this was

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:59.359
on March the 12th, so still about two weeks before the UK, for example, actually went into lockdown.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.080
And now we've got all of that additional labelling added. Again, going back to that research, these

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:08.400
are the key bits of information that are going to be the first thing that someone encountering this

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:12.000
chart focuses on. And they're going to set the scene for everything else that they take away

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.880
from it. So we've got a title, a very active title, descriptive narrative title, that most

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:21.280
Western countries were on the same coronavirus trajectories. Hong Kong and Singapore, by

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:25.599
contrast, have managed to slow the spread. So straight away, you've got a message which grabs

00:11:25.599 --> 00:11:29.520
you, which brings you in, and which tells you something that is happening in the world. The

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:34.320
fact that there's a chart here as well is almost incidental. I mean, maybe I'm exaggerating there.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:40.400
But the point is, whether or not you are someone who builds and works with database multiple times

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:46.559
a day, or someone who last really spent any time with charts when you're aged 16 and doing some

00:11:46.559 --> 00:11:52.000
compulsory maths or science education, whichever of those groups you fall into, the words here tell

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.719
you what's going on. And so if you are someone who doesn't consider themselves a chart person,

00:11:56.719 --> 00:12:01.119
you've got your entry point. You can now understand the geometry of the chart. You can

00:12:01.119 --> 00:12:04.799
work out what's going on with the lines, with the shape, with the space, with the colour,

00:12:04.799 --> 00:12:10.400
because you know what message it's trying to tell. If the chart simply said cumulative number of

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:16.080
cases by number of days in some case as the title, that's a hell of a lot more technical. There's a

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:20.640
lot more jargon, and it's going to be much less accessible to people who are not familiar with

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:25.359
charts. The other thing we've obviously got here is these annotations towards the right-hand side,

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:29.760
actually explaining some of the stuff you can see on the chart. So this is more geared towards

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:36.400
someone who has not been following the pandemic and COVID data in a huge amount of detail.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:42.479
They immediately have the queries that they would have had of this chart answered. So they can see,

00:12:42.479 --> 00:12:49.440
oh, right, so Japan, its line is further down. The virus is spreading less fast there and less

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:53.440
widely. But we can see that it's not quite clear yet whether the spread has actually slowed in

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:58.239
Japan or they're not doing enough testing. Korea, we can see, which was of course the

00:12:58.239 --> 00:13:03.039
big focus here as we were looking for how countries could get off that steep curve and flatten.

00:13:03.039 --> 00:13:07.440
We've got an explanation there about how it has slowed its spread from the initial pace.

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:10.320
And you can also look at Singapore and Hong Kong and see what they've done right.

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:16.559
So that text, when we looked at what people were talking about around the context of this graphic

00:13:16.559 --> 00:13:21.280
on social media and on the Financial Times website, that text was the key part that really

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:25.440
seemed to cut through and cause people to keep coming back to this chart and indeed to share

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:31.200
this chart with other people. So the first lesson of the pandemic for me, I think, was that

00:13:31.919 --> 00:13:38.320
using text and other annotation is really critical for making sure a chart goes from being a chart

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:46.000
for dataviz people, shall we say, to a chart that is truly accessible to a really mass audience of

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:52.559
people who haven't been, they're not involved in charts and data every day. And suddenly,

00:13:52.559 --> 00:13:56.559
this is the sort of democratization of charts by using text to make them more accessible.

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:02.479
The next lesson, and this is for me one of the most fundamental lessons anyone can learn

00:14:02.479 --> 00:14:08.159
in the process of building dataviz, is that there's a big difference between making the

00:14:08.159 --> 00:14:13.679
smartest version of a chart you possibly can and the clearest version of a chart you possibly can.

00:14:13.679 --> 00:14:16.960
As with everything, there are obviously exceptions where you can do both of these things,

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:21.200
but during the pandemic, I think there have been several examples of how these really do,

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:24.400
these really are in tension with one another a lot of the time.

00:14:26.719 --> 00:14:30.799
So sometimes, and this was more the case, I think, in the earlier part of my career,

00:14:31.919 --> 00:14:36.000
but it's still a recurring theme, and I think this is something that a lot of people

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.239
here today will recognize as well. Sometimes we can get into the habit of thinking that

00:14:40.239 --> 00:14:46.559
effective data visualization is about optimizing for precision and objectivity. There's a sort of

00:14:47.200 --> 00:14:53.280
list of technical tasks, and if you nail every one of them, you'll make the perfect chart.

00:14:53.919 --> 00:14:59.039
You're using maths and geometry to arrive at the best solution. It's a very sort of technical

00:14:59.679 --> 00:15:06.000
and structured process. But then I actually publish a chart, and it suddenly becomes

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.080
very clear that that is simply not the case. That is a convenient but very rarely true

00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:16.080
description of what we should be aiming for when we make a data visualization.

00:15:17.679 --> 00:15:22.960
So I'm going to come back to this same chart and talk through all of the clever technical

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:28.960
things that I thought I was doing with this chart when I made it, and then how the chart then

00:15:29.679 --> 00:15:34.799
encountered reality, shall we say. A lot of my assumptions were turned on their head.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:41.119
So the first difference, and I'm just going to flick back between these two charts. This is the

00:15:41.119 --> 00:15:46.880
one that I've shown you already. This was the data plotted on a logarithmic y-axis. The point of this

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:52.479
was to say, well, we know that the pandemic, especially in the early stage, spreads exponentially.

00:15:53.359 --> 00:16:01.679
So the shape of the curves on this chart, if we plotted it on a linear axis, on a linear scale,

00:16:01.679 --> 00:16:06.479
they would all be arcing upwards from gentle slopes to steep slopes. And to me, you're using

00:16:06.479 --> 00:16:11.200
a lot of visual bandwidth there just to show something that we assume is the default, that

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:14.239
all of these curves are going to be getting steeper and steeper in these early weeks.

00:16:14.799 --> 00:16:20.320
So by going for a log scale, you sort of free up more bandwidth, as it were, in the reader's head,

00:16:20.320 --> 00:16:25.039
and you allow them to focus on what matters, which is you can now do the key thing that

00:16:25.039 --> 00:16:29.679
readers at this stage wanted to do, which is compare the trajectories of different countries

00:16:29.679 --> 00:16:34.960
on a straight line. You can look at this and say, OK, the virus seems to be spreading more quickly

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:40.799
in Spain than in France, and France, in turn, more quickly than the UK. You can also, because it's a

00:16:40.799 --> 00:16:46.719
straight line, you can forecast out ahead and work out where the rate of cases in your country is

00:16:46.719 --> 00:16:51.440
going to be a few days or a week further down the line. You can answer that critical question

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:56.559
that we set out to answer here, if we refer back to my colleague's email, which is how are countries

00:16:56.559 --> 00:17:00.719
doing compared to Italy? You can answer that much more easily with these straight lines that are

00:17:00.719 --> 00:17:05.520
easy to extrapolate than with the curves, where it's harder to work out exactly where a line will

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:11.040
be at a certain point in time. So my thinking here was all framed around this idea that when

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:16.000
someone's looking at this chart, there's a whole sort of framework they're operating in that

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:20.880
determines what their takeaway message is, is about are these two countries or three countries

00:17:20.880 --> 00:17:26.959
on the same course, or how many days until the country I'm interested in is at a certain level

00:17:26.959 --> 00:17:33.839
of cases that I know sort of means something. And therefore, that they're not thinking, well, how

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:38.800
many pixels represent 100 cases? They're not worried about what's going on on the y-axis.

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:44.640
They're looking for more of a sort of overarching message. However, let's have a look at some of

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:49.520
the feedback that started pouring into that. And I'll say just as a quick aside here, for anyone

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:54.160
who isn't in the habit of publishing their work on social media, and I know it's not for everyone,

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:59.680
and there are certainly some sub-optimal features of Twitter, shall we say, but it's an incredible

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:05.920
way to work out what does and doesn't work in a chart, and to gauge the sort of reaction again of

00:18:06.479 --> 00:18:13.439
both chart people and non-chart people very quickly. So I was inundated with messages

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:20.319
around responding to these charts for week after week after week, and continue to be this year.

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:24.800
But this was a snapshot of some of the initial feedback to that chart. Now, obviously,

00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:32.160
loads of people understood the log axis fine, but any critical feedback is always worth

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:36.959
paying attention to. And the fact that the majority of people got it doesn't negate the fact that

00:18:36.959 --> 00:18:42.079
plenty of people didn't. So lots of people here, very confused by what's going on in the y-axis.

00:18:42.079 --> 00:18:46.239
Some of them perhaps know what a log scale is, but just thought it wasn't clearly explained.

00:18:46.239 --> 00:18:51.280
Others clearly are just baffled, and that's not a reaction you want with your chart.

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:58.640
However, my response to that was not to just think, oh, right, okay, back to the drawing

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:03.839
board, start again, it's got to be linear, people aren't getting this. My response was to think,

00:19:03.839 --> 00:19:10.479
okay, I've got a, I'm in an advantageous position here that I'm on Twitter where I'm presenting

00:19:10.479 --> 00:19:16.560
these charts, and this is a space where I can continue these conversations. So what I did was

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:23.040
I immediately posted a long explanation, or not too long, but a relatively thorough explanation

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:29.599
of exactly why logarithmic y-axes were well suited to visualizing data that grows exponentially.

00:19:30.719 --> 00:19:36.719
That got a very good response, and we followed up on that at the FT by actually making a whole

00:19:36.719 --> 00:19:40.560
video explainer which talked about all of the decisions we were making when we made these charts

00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:46.560
and how to understand them. And this seemed to work really, really well in terms of softening

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:53.439
some of that initial confusion that some people had to the chart. And my favorite thing about this

00:19:53.439 --> 00:19:58.640
is that what you get when you do this kind of work, what you'll see when you explain things

00:19:58.640 --> 00:20:03.040
clearly and have them in the public domain, whether it's Twitter, Facebook, whatever,

00:20:03.599 --> 00:20:10.239
is your audience will start helping you explain this stuff to other people.

00:20:10.959 --> 00:20:15.599
So what we started to see quite soon was these are other people jumping into the replies to me

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:20.640
explaining to the people who've been confused, look, this is a log scale, this is what they do,

00:20:21.199 --> 00:20:26.239
don't worry about it, and actually pointing people to the video where I'd explain this.

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:33.199
So instead of thinking, well, you know, I've just published the chart, I'm done,

00:20:33.199 --> 00:20:38.319
I'm going to walk away, by sort of staying in that conversation around the chart,

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:44.959
I was able to ensure that as few people as possible actually remained confused,

00:20:44.959 --> 00:20:47.599
and to really try and improve understanding of log scales full stop.

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:52.800
Just as a quick aside, something I find quite amusing when I look back at these messages is

00:20:52.800 --> 00:20:57.920
that you'll see on the left-hand side there, two of the people who'd been confused by the log scale,

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:01.520
well, one of them, their account is now suspended, and the other one,

00:21:01.520 --> 00:21:05.040
their account no longer exists. So I like to think of that as being a little

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:10.560
example that people who don't understand log scales have other failings in life,

00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:14.160
shall we say, that lead them to be kicked off Twitter. Anyway, back to the important stuff.

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:19.920
All of this about log scales and people perhaps initially not understanding them,

00:21:19.920 --> 00:21:22.719
but gradually getting their heads around them, brings me on to what,

00:21:22.719 --> 00:21:28.319
in a huge sea of contenders, is actually my favourite chart of the pandemic, and that is this.

00:21:29.599 --> 00:21:34.319
What you're looking at here is data from Google Trends, which for the unfamiliar is

00:21:35.040 --> 00:21:38.640
measuring how much search interest on Google there is for topics over time.

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:45.199
And what we see here is this is the numbers of people worldwide searching for log scale on Google,

00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:51.359
and I've got that going back for the last five years or so, so from late 2015 through to

00:21:53.199 --> 00:22:00.079
early, well, the start of, sorry, through to, so from late 2015 through to mid-2020.

00:22:00.079 --> 00:22:04.719
And what you see there is a big spike, searches for log scale in that five-year period

00:22:04.719 --> 00:22:10.880
reached their peak on around the 22nd of March 2020. And coincidentally, that was about a week

00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:17.439
after we started publishing these log scale charts on the FT, and the interest, the numbers

00:22:17.439 --> 00:22:21.680
of people looking at those charts had really ramped up over that week. So I don't think it's

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:29.520
unreasonable for me and for us at the FT to think that the proliferation of log scale charts and our

00:22:29.520 --> 00:22:34.640
use of explainers around them really did help actually educate a hell of a lot of people on

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:39.839
what log scales are. And I know that from other anecdotal evidence as well. I had sort of school

00:22:39.839 --> 00:22:43.839
friends who I'd not spoken to for 15 years getting in touch saying they were explaining my charts to

00:22:43.839 --> 00:22:49.920
their mum and that kind of thing. So it was a real demonstration that by sticking around and actually

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:55.520
explaining what your chart is showing to people, you can really help people become more visually

00:22:55.520 --> 00:23:02.400
literate. So the lesson there, yeah, is that if there is confusion around a chart that you've made,

00:23:03.119 --> 00:23:07.359
that's on you. It's no good just saying, oh, how do these people not understand log scales?

00:23:07.439 --> 00:23:13.199
You've got to do the work to make sure that the people, you've got to do the work to make sure

00:23:13.199 --> 00:23:18.239
that your audience is not left confused. And the key point here for me as well is doing this

00:23:18.239 --> 00:23:23.040
additional explanation in situ, doing this explanation where the chart appeared. It's not

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:28.640
much use publishing a chart over here and then a few days later explaining how it was meant to work

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:34.079
over here. You've got to try and do that where your audience is so that they are not going to

00:23:34.079 --> 00:23:41.680
get lost along the way and walk away scratching their head. But there's more. The reactions to

00:23:41.680 --> 00:23:47.760
these log scales were not purely about the log scales or about the geometry, about the space,

00:23:47.760 --> 00:23:52.319
about the numbers. When you look at some of these other responses, a lot of them were much more

00:23:53.199 --> 00:23:59.839
qualitative or they were quite personal. In some cases, they were even political. So I'm sure I

00:23:59.839 --> 00:24:05.439
don't need to explain to everyone that the pandemic, COVID, has all become quite politicized,

00:24:05.439 --> 00:24:12.719
quite partisan over the last year. There are camps of pro-maskers and anti-maskers, pro-lockdown,

00:24:12.719 --> 00:24:18.400
anti-lockdown, all of this stuff. And it turns out that the use of log scales in charts is actually

00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:23.439
another example of this. So we had some people saying that they felt like the use of a log scale

00:24:24.319 --> 00:24:32.479
was sort of dampening the impact of increased numbers of cases. So a line went up and up and

00:24:32.479 --> 00:24:39.599
up. It then started to gradually flatten as the rate of increase slowed, even if the numbers

00:24:39.599 --> 00:24:47.359
were still going up. So people felt like we were diminishing, we were downplaying the impact

00:24:47.359 --> 00:24:52.880
of increased spread as time went on because those lines were becoming flatter, whereas if

00:24:52.880 --> 00:24:57.280
they were linear, they would be going straight upwards. And yeah, people really felt that we

00:24:57.280 --> 00:25:01.760
were perhaps trying to make some kind of political point here and trying to suggest that in the UK,

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:09.040
for example, things weren't as bad as they were. So the clear takeaway from that seems to be that

00:25:09.040 --> 00:25:14.560
quite apart from people reacting to the actual data and geometry in your charts,

00:25:14.560 --> 00:25:20.239
they're going to come in with all sorts of baggage, as it were, in terms of their understandings and

00:25:20.239 --> 00:25:24.479
feelings about the subject matter. And there may be decisions that you made in the construction of

00:25:24.479 --> 00:25:30.640
your charts that you felt were purely technical, purely to do with data viz, but people are

00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:35.520
actually going to read into that a lot more than what you intended. So generally, there seem to be

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:41.359
two camps of people roughly who would look at these charts. There are people who, like us in

00:25:41.359 --> 00:25:45.199
this session today, who would just look at these numbers and think, all right, okay, what's going

00:25:45.199 --> 00:25:51.680
on there? A very sort of analytical way of analysing the chart. But there was a huge number

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:55.760
of others who, and I think this goes back to my first point really as well about the use of text

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:59.760
and how people understand charts, they would just take away a single overarching message from these

00:25:59.760 --> 00:26:04.959
charts. And so they would look at something where the lines were sort of becoming a bit more gentle,

00:26:04.959 --> 00:26:08.239
and they would think, oh, this chart is trying to say things aren't actually that bad at all.

00:26:09.199 --> 00:26:12.319
And so it was just a really interesting demonstration of how you kind of need to

00:26:12.319 --> 00:26:16.560
cater to those needs. You don't want someone to have a negative reaction to your chart

00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:21.760
based on some design choice that you made, even if you hadn't realised what impact it was going to

00:26:21.760 --> 00:26:29.040
have. So yeah, this can lead people to completely sort of throw out the baby with the bathwater.

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:35.359
They'll decide that this chart is wrong, it's worthless, it's junk, because it has this,

00:26:35.359 --> 00:26:40.800
it jars with their understanding of the subject matter. So this is the next lesson for us,

00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:48.079
which was that information visualisation and database is about much more than just pixels

00:26:48.079 --> 00:26:53.359
on a page and geometry and shape and space and colour. It's about the whole feeling that

00:26:53.359 --> 00:26:58.719
something creates and whether that meshes with or jars with someone's perceptions of the topic

00:26:58.719 --> 00:27:05.760
at hand. So we need to think about that when we're producing a chart, especially on a divisive or

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:11.599
sort of sensitive topic like this, and minimise the risk that someone's going to react badly

00:27:11.599 --> 00:27:14.239
because of some choices that we've consciously made in the geometry.

00:27:15.520 --> 00:27:19.040
If someone's objecting to the data itself, that's their point, you know, if someone was looking at

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:26.400
this chart and saying, oh, why are you showing COVID cases going up when the pandemic is over?

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:31.920
Well, that would be flat out wrong, because COVID cases were going up. But if someone's objecting to

00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:36.239
the use of a different scale, for example, and the tone, the feel that that gives to your chart,

00:27:36.239 --> 00:27:40.239
I think that's, that's not unreasonable. Their feelings are what their feelings are.

00:27:40.239 --> 00:27:44.239
And it's important for us to consider that when we're designing our charts.

00:27:45.359 --> 00:27:50.959
So what we did in the end of the FT was we turned these static graphics that we've been producing

00:27:50.959 --> 00:27:56.239
every day with a log scale into an interactive piece where you can choose between log or linear.

00:27:56.719 --> 00:28:03.599
So anyone then complaining about not understanding or being misled by the use of a log scale,

00:28:03.599 --> 00:28:08.800
for example, could then flip between the two toggle between the two on our page here. And that's what

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:11.280
many, many, many people have done over the course of the last year.

00:28:12.959 --> 00:28:18.000
The next point, and this comes back to what I was saying earlier about the value of something like

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:23.520
social media or whatever platform you're publishing your charts on. And I want to talk about how you

00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:29.199
can gain an enormous amount from thinking about database, again, as a fundamental act of

00:28:29.199 --> 00:28:36.160
communication as a dialogue. So instead of just throwing your chart out there and walking away

00:28:36.160 --> 00:28:41.280
and sort of explosions in the background, as it were, stick around, get into the conversation and

00:28:41.280 --> 00:28:45.839
see what you can learn and what you can gain from those conversations about the work that you've

00:28:45.839 --> 00:28:53.280
done. And I just, I think it's, I feel so fortunate as it were to have had the number of

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:58.640
interactions I've had with people all over the world from all walks of life, all levels of data

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:04.800
and visual literacy about the charts that I've built, because I have now an enormous, an enormous

00:29:04.800 --> 00:29:08.560
amount of information on what people have liked, what people haven't liked, what people have

00:29:08.560 --> 00:29:13.119
struggled with, what people have been challenged by but risen to, what people have just sort of

00:29:13.119 --> 00:29:17.199
thrown their hands up at and not liked at all. And so getting into those conversations, I think

00:29:17.199 --> 00:29:21.760
it's absolutely critical, whether you're publishing this as a journalist to a mass audience, whether

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:29.920
it's to colleagues at your workplace, wherever it is. So to do that, one thing we did very explicitly

00:29:29.920 --> 00:29:35.839
from quite early on in our sort of visual coverage of the pandemic was we explicitly solicited this

00:29:35.839 --> 00:29:40.160
kind of feedback. Because sure, as I've shown you with some of those responses to the log scales,

00:29:40.640 --> 00:29:44.560
the nature of Twitter is that you will get feedback whether you ask for it or not.

00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:50.479
But I think as anyone who's thought about this for any amount of time knows, the quality of

00:29:50.479 --> 00:29:55.599
feedback you'll get goes up through the roof, or exponentially one might say, when you actually

00:29:55.599 --> 00:30:00.560
ask for that. Because first of all, there are a hell of a lot of people, the majority of people

00:30:01.439 --> 00:30:09.359
in fact, aren't just going to randomly hit a stranger with a load of thoughts on the work

00:30:09.359 --> 00:30:14.880
that they've just done. A lot of people are polite, or they're shy, or this is just not

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:19.680
how they work online. Whereas when you actively go out there and say, let us know what you think

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:22.800
about this, the stuff that we've been doing here, what do you think of these charts? Did they work?

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:27.439
Did they not? Any other thoughts you have? First of all, you're opening the door, you're telling

00:30:27.439 --> 00:30:33.199
these people who are maybe more introverted, or just don't see it as their place to comment,

00:30:33.199 --> 00:30:40.800
you're telling them that, yeah, we want to hear your thoughts. But you're also, I think making

00:30:40.800 --> 00:30:45.760
that any criticism you receive much more likely to be constructive, because people now know that

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:50.239
their criticism is going to be acted upon, and they're not just sort of shouting into the screen.

00:30:50.959 --> 00:30:57.040
So we would explicitly ask for feedback over email, over Twitter direct messages and replies,

00:30:57.040 --> 00:31:01.760
we actually ended up setting up a completely separate inbox, just for people to talk to us

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:07.920
about these charts. And this is just a snapshot from one day in April. And this was a full screen

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:14.640
of Gmail. But this one day's messages spanned more than one full screen. So we've, I think this was,

00:31:14.640 --> 00:31:20.479
we had about 100 messages in one day about this chart. And I don't think people will be able to

00:31:20.479 --> 00:31:24.800
read the text there. But if I just talk through the range of stuff we were getting here, we've

00:31:24.800 --> 00:31:29.119
got people pointing us to data sources that we didn't know about before, for countries in the

00:31:29.119 --> 00:31:34.319
world that we didn't previously include in our charts. We've got people pointing out things that

00:31:34.319 --> 00:31:38.800
they struggled with and would like us to change in our charts. We've got people just thanking us for

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:43.199
doing these charts. We've got people who may be a bit less polite, they're just saying, I didn't

00:31:43.199 --> 00:31:48.239
like this. We've got people asking us to include different charts, we've got people coming to us

00:31:48.239 --> 00:31:56.000
with story ideas, an enormous range of information that both as both in terms of how we iterate on

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:02.000
this database and how we just cover the pandemic more broadly were incredibly, incredibly valuable.

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:06.800
And none of this information would have come to us if we hadn't set up this inbox, if we hadn't

00:32:06.800 --> 00:32:12.239
asked people to send this to us. So the lesson there, I think, is very clear, which is that

00:32:13.599 --> 00:32:20.160
we, if we want to, you know, do our, do the best that we can do as data visualization practitioners,

00:32:20.160 --> 00:32:27.920
both in terms of improving the work that we do through feedback and in terms of just reaching,

00:32:27.920 --> 00:32:32.719
effectively reaching as many people as possible and making them feel like charts and databases are

00:32:32.719 --> 00:32:39.359
for them and not just for data nerds. Continued communication is absolutely critical. So I might

00:32:39.359 --> 00:32:45.520
suggest, for example, that you might want to put a contact email or Twitter handle or whatever works

00:32:45.520 --> 00:32:50.319
best for you on your chart sometimes so that wherever someone encounters this piece of work

00:32:50.319 --> 00:32:54.800
in the wild, they'll know they can come to you and they can give you thoughts. I just feel like it's

00:32:54.800 --> 00:32:59.839
so invaluable and you will learn so much about what does and doesn't work and the shades of grey in

00:32:59.839 --> 00:33:05.439
between by doing this. Whereas I think there's often a tendency for us in database to see our

00:33:05.439 --> 00:33:09.520
job as just making a thing and then we put the thing out there and we forget about it. But really,

00:33:09.520 --> 00:33:14.800
really, if there's one thing I can get to you from today, it's don't do that, stick around, enjoy the

00:33:14.800 --> 00:33:22.479
chat. The next point, big learning curve for me, and again that audience feedback was absolutely

00:33:22.479 --> 00:33:29.839
critical to this, was the risk of trying to be too clever, trying to be too technical with solutions

00:33:30.479 --> 00:33:38.079
to database problems and essentially losing people along the way and losing trust along the way. So

00:33:38.079 --> 00:33:42.000
the term blinding with science, I'm sure most of you are familiar with, but for those who aren't,

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:46.800
it's the idea that you're telling someone about something in an overly complex or technical way

00:33:47.599 --> 00:33:54.079
so that regardless of the result of what you've done, they end up going away scratching their

00:33:54.079 --> 00:33:59.119
head. They're not quite sure because of the terminology, because of the methodology,

00:33:59.119 --> 00:34:03.599
they're not quite sure what you've done and I think there's often a risk with that in database.

00:34:03.599 --> 00:34:11.840
So the question that we had, this was still back in the spring, was could we improve the way

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:17.840
we drew the lines on our charts so that instead of using a simple seven-day rolling average as we

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:24.320
had been doing, we got slightly smoother lines but we also got lines where the final data point

00:34:24.320 --> 00:34:30.159
on the chart was a more faithful reflection of the final data point in real life. Because of course

00:34:30.159 --> 00:34:34.719
the problem when you're doing a seven-day average, whether you align that seven-day average to the

00:34:34.719 --> 00:34:40.239
right, to the middle, to the left, is it's never going to be an especially close representation

00:34:40.239 --> 00:34:46.479
of the last data point you have because it's being influenced by the other six. And so the

00:34:46.479 --> 00:34:51.840
issue we were having is the numbers in our headlines, in our news stories at the FT, would

00:34:51.840 --> 00:34:56.159
always be referring to that last data point, the thing that has just happened, but our charts were

00:34:56.159 --> 00:35:01.760
referring to the seven-day average which was, while cases were going up, always lower than that and so

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:05.919
we would have this tension where the numbers on our charts didn't quite reflect the numbers of news.

00:35:06.879 --> 00:35:12.560
So what we decided to do was look at whether we could optimize the way we actually draw the lines

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:16.639
on the chart so that they're still smooth, as you get with an average, but they also actually

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:22.159
more faithfully reflect the very latest data point you have. So for those of you who have only ever

00:35:22.159 --> 00:35:26.719
seen seven-day average charts of COVID data, this is what the underlying data actually looks like.

00:35:26.719 --> 00:35:34.320
It's incredibly noisy, you get these huge peeps and troughs, new daily cases will drop to zero

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:40.080
and then shoot up to a thousand the next day because the way that this data is actually

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:46.479
collected and reported leads to enormous differences in the numbers you get from day to day.

00:35:47.199 --> 00:35:51.679
There's weekly cyclicality, there's all sorts of stuff going on. So we definitely didn't want the

00:35:51.679 --> 00:35:56.800
data to look like this. Now, of course, the last point of each line here would reflect reality,

00:35:56.800 --> 00:36:01.120
would reflect the last data point we had, but it's far too noisy, we couldn't publish that.

00:36:01.679 --> 00:36:05.439
So here's the rolling average method we have been using, much clearer, much smoother,

00:36:05.439 --> 00:36:10.000
you can see exactly what's going on, you get clear trends over time, you can see here,

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:15.840
for example, that Italy had reached its peak and started coming back down, but the last data point

00:36:15.840 --> 00:36:19.120
on each of these lines didn't necessarily match up with the last data point that had been recorded.

00:36:20.320 --> 00:36:25.840
So what we considered was a smoothing spline, so it keeps that smoothness of the lines,

00:36:25.840 --> 00:36:30.639
it's still relatively easy to discern what's going on in one country and compare it to another,

00:36:30.639 --> 00:36:35.760
but the last data point is now, because of how the splines are calculated, much closer to the

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:40.399
last data point that had been recorded. And you can see that in this next chart. So we actually

00:36:40.399 --> 00:36:49.040
measured how close to the final reported data point was the last data point of each line when

00:36:49.040 --> 00:36:52.800
we use this method. On the left hand side, you've got a simple rolling average, on the right hand

00:36:52.800 --> 00:36:57.120
side, you've got the spline, and you can see that the data points are much closer to the real

00:36:57.120 --> 00:37:03.040
reported value on the right. So we decided, let's switch over to the spline. And we did, again,

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:11.760
a long explainer of why we'd done this, setting out that need to better represent the most recent

00:37:11.760 --> 00:37:17.919
data while keeping smoothness, big explanation out in the public for anyone to see. And I then,

00:37:17.919 --> 00:37:22.399
again, following my own advice, asked people what they think. And here's the kind of responses we

00:37:22.399 --> 00:37:26.959
got. And what you'll notice is there were sort of two quite clearly different camps here.

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:32.719
On the left, top left, we've got a couple of people saying the spline's much better. Yeah,

00:37:32.719 --> 00:37:37.439
I'm very devoted to splining myself, for example. And the thing I should point out immediately about

00:37:37.439 --> 00:37:41.439
that is that these two people, Peter and Micah, I don't know if either of them are actually

00:37:42.239 --> 00:37:48.239
watching along today, are both data scientists to some degree. So I think anyone who's heard

00:37:48.239 --> 00:37:55.439
of splines felt very positive about that as an idea. But then we get some different feedback.

00:37:55.439 --> 00:37:59.520
In the upper right, we've got someone saying the rolling average is much easier for the average

00:37:59.520 --> 00:38:05.199
person to understand. And in the lower left, we've got someone with a data science background,

00:38:05.199 --> 00:38:11.040
but still saying that the rolling average probably makes more sense. And then in the lower left,

00:38:11.040 --> 00:38:14.560
we actually have one of the epidemiologists in the UK working on the development of

00:38:15.199 --> 00:38:22.320
the vaccines talking about how this is for the general public. The audience for this work is

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:27.040
a mass audience. It's an audience with a very mixed visual and data literacy. And it's much

00:38:27.040 --> 00:38:32.639
easier for people to get their head around a seven-day average than a spline. So different

00:38:32.639 --> 00:38:40.560
people with different personal contexts had very different views on this. So the takeaway that we

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:44.479
had, again, from this was that you have to prioritize the ease of understanding. You may

00:38:44.479 --> 00:38:49.919
have come up with an incredibly technical, nifty solution that, on the basis of any sort of

00:38:49.919 --> 00:38:55.919
quantitative tests, works better. But if that is going to confuse people along the way, that is a

00:38:55.919 --> 00:39:00.879
problem. And again, for me, the fundamental goal of my data visualizations is communication with

00:39:00.879 --> 00:39:08.399
a mass audience. And I would rather have clear communication and as many people as possible

00:39:08.399 --> 00:39:13.520
understanding, remembering, and wanting to share these charts than to have something which is

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:18.800
5% more correct, shall we say, but that loses a lot of people along the way.

00:39:20.639 --> 00:39:24.879
The final lesson that we've learned, and just in the last couple of weeks, I think, in our work

00:39:24.879 --> 00:39:33.520
on the pandemic has been the importance and just the way that you can use animation to tell a story

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:37.840
much, much more effectively than telling that same story in a static chart.

00:39:38.959 --> 00:39:43.120
And so I've done a couple of bits of animation over the last couple of years, which have been

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:49.760
especially effective. And I think the lesson I've really learned from this is that the sense of

00:39:49.760 --> 00:39:56.959
tension and of anticipation that you can build up when you do animation well can produce a much,

00:39:56.959 --> 00:40:01.840
much stronger response from people, a much stronger reaction than doing exactly the same

00:40:02.159 --> 00:40:07.199
as a static chart. So I'm going to show you two examples of that. There are examples that some of

00:40:07.199 --> 00:40:14.639
you may have seen in recent days, which are where I wanted to make the point that COVID really is

00:40:14.639 --> 00:40:20.560
considerably worse, for example, than a bad flu. So here's the first chart. And what we're looking

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:24.479
at here, again, this is a GIF. It's an animation. It's going to loop. So if you miss it the first

00:40:24.479 --> 00:40:29.600
time, we'll see it the second time. We're looking at the weekly rates of people admitted into ICU,

00:40:29.600 --> 00:40:36.159
so intensive care units, in England with flu in a typical winter over the last few years,

00:40:36.159 --> 00:40:41.919
and then contrasting that with what we've seen this year for COVID. And you'll see quite clearly

00:40:41.919 --> 00:40:46.879
that flu admissions in the past were, even when we thought they were high, so even when we had

00:40:46.879 --> 00:40:53.760
what at the time were seen as record bad flu winters, those figures were much, much lower

00:40:53.760 --> 00:40:59.280
than what we've seen over the last month or two in England with COVID. So this was really an

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:06.560
attempt to put to bed this myth, this idea that, oh, COVID's just, you know, it's just flu rebranded.

00:41:06.560 --> 00:41:10.399
It's just a new version of what we've seen before, and show that this really is a completely different

00:41:10.399 --> 00:41:15.439
beast. Now, some people would come back to this and say, well, you know, we're just testing a lot

00:41:15.439 --> 00:41:20.159
more for COVID this year. So that's why we see the numbers. We see much higher numbers than we

00:41:20.239 --> 00:41:25.360
usually would with flu. But again, I had another animated response to that, which is to show the

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:31.760
total numbers of people in ICU, in intensive care, in London, London, UK, for any reason,

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:38.560
and compare that again from winter to winter. So in a typical year, even during a bad flu season,

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:44.080
the numbers of people in intensive care in London never go above about 750. So again,

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:49.040
this is whether they're in there for flu, whether they're in there for a heart attack, for a stroke,

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:54.800
any of that. But the numbers of people in there for all causes never really go above about 750,

00:41:54.800 --> 00:41:59.919
and are typically around 700. Whereas this year, they've gone up above 1200. And in fact,

00:41:59.919 --> 00:42:04.639
in recent days, have gone closer to 1400. So almost double the number of people in intensive

00:42:04.639 --> 00:42:08.800
care in London this year than the usual year. And unless there's been a sudden surge in the

00:42:08.800 --> 00:42:14.000
numbers of people falling down multiple flights of stairs, we can point to the one thing that

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:19.760
is different about this year, which is COVID. But the point is, for what I consider to be a really

00:42:19.760 --> 00:42:26.320
important topic here, which is correcting relatively widely held myths, that what we were

00:42:26.320 --> 00:42:31.040
seeing this winter was nothing out of the ordinary, and therefore, we don't need to be in lockdown,

00:42:31.040 --> 00:42:35.919
we don't need any restrictions, because this is just like any other winter. You gain an enormous

00:42:35.919 --> 00:42:44.159
amount by producing this as an animation, it's a much more engaging piece of work. And this

00:42:44.159 --> 00:42:50.879
graphic on Twitter alone has now been seen by more than 10 million people, which is far more people

00:42:50.879 --> 00:42:57.439
have seen this graphic than any other chart that we produce at the FT all year on social media. And

00:42:57.439 --> 00:43:01.679
that I think, and in fact, it's not just what I think a lot of the responses on social media

00:43:01.679 --> 00:43:08.080
have explicitly pointed to this, the use of animation was enormously pivotal to that in

00:43:08.080 --> 00:43:12.879
terms of how it grabs attention more than a static chart, in terms of how it builds suspense, and in

00:43:12.879 --> 00:43:16.560
terms of how you get that shock, that surprise factor at the end when you compare the two.

00:43:17.520 --> 00:43:23.520
So the key point there being, where it's suitable, animation is an incredibly powerful technique to

00:43:23.520 --> 00:43:27.919
use to convey a message. Now, I think it should be used sparingly. If you suddenly make everything

00:43:27.919 --> 00:43:35.439
animated, it's like the old days of 90s internet where you've got pop-ups everywhere. Everything's

00:43:35.439 --> 00:43:38.959
too noisy, it's hard to actually get across your key point and everything gets drowned out.

00:43:38.959 --> 00:43:42.080
But using animation sparingly, I think, is an incredibly powerful technique.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:49.760
So all of that is to say that the last 12 months, I think, have been an incredible crash course for

00:43:49.760 --> 00:43:54.959
me and for our team at the FT in terms of really getting to the fundamentals of how people do

00:43:54.959 --> 00:43:59.600
read charts and, therefore, what we should be thinking about when we make charts, what we should

00:43:59.600 --> 00:44:07.360
be focusing on and prioritizing. And coming into this year, I think my assumption, and a lot of

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:11.600
people here, I'm sure, the assumption would have been that people read charts a bit like this. They

00:44:11.600 --> 00:44:17.520
get out their protractor, their set square, their ruler, and their compass, and it's all about

00:44:17.520 --> 00:44:24.479
precision and people are really focusing on individual pixels and where different elements

00:44:24.479 --> 00:44:28.800
are in your plot when they're trying to take away their message. They're almost trying to pass the

00:44:28.800 --> 00:44:34.000
data set back out of your chart and so you, as the practitioner, should really be focusing on

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:42.080
the most high fidelity, most clear encoding of that data as possible. But the reality, I think,

00:44:42.080 --> 00:44:46.000
is actually a bit more like this. It's a bit more like people going to a movie theater

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:54.000
and sitting back and watching. They are coming to a chart to see something, to see some kind of story,

00:44:54.399 --> 00:44:58.159
to get a message, to take away something that is playing out in front of them.

00:44:59.040 --> 00:45:02.879
In some cases, literally with the animation, but in other cases, it's just a line chart.

00:45:02.879 --> 00:45:08.879
But it's a line chart where they're not focusing on tiny differences between data points on the

00:45:08.879 --> 00:45:13.199
chart. They're focusing on what is this top line message in the title, what's the takeaway here,

00:45:13.199 --> 00:45:16.959
and what are the other sweeping trends that this chart is conveying.

00:45:16.959 --> 00:45:20.639
They're not poring over it, trying to extract the values from every pixel on the page.

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:24.479
So to summarize, the key lessons I think I've learned here, and I think these are

00:45:24.479 --> 00:45:30.879
lessons that I'm going to be using for the rest of my career. First of all, text is critical.

00:45:30.879 --> 00:45:36.399
I know we're all in the data viz industry. We make charts. But if we don't get the text right,

00:45:36.399 --> 00:45:40.959
none of the rest really matters. People will be lost. They'll be confused. It will be a disaster.

00:45:41.679 --> 00:45:45.919
The second point, we have to take responsibility. If someone is confused about our chart,

00:45:46.080 --> 00:45:50.560
if someone is confused about our chart, that's our fault. And the best thing we can do to combat

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:57.439
that is to include explanations in situ around where that chart appears to make sure that there's

00:45:57.439 --> 00:46:01.840
as little risk as possible of confusion. On a similar note, we need to be considering

00:46:02.560 --> 00:46:07.280
what are people's beliefs, feelings, emotions, sentiments around this subject matter, and how

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:11.840
could they color their reaction to this chart? How can we design this chart in as neutral a way as

00:46:11.840 --> 00:46:16.959
possible in that sense so that at least if anyone does have any issues with their chart,

00:46:16.959 --> 00:46:24.080
it's because they don't like the data. It's not because they feel put off or hurt somehow by the

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:28.000
way we've actually conveyed the information. The next step, and I think, again, one of the

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:32.239
most important, don't just publish and vanish. Stick around. Get involved in the conversation.

00:46:32.239 --> 00:46:37.439
You will learn so much about how people are understanding your chart that you can incorporate

00:46:37.439 --> 00:46:43.840
into the next one you make. And make sure that your chart above all else is easy to understand.

00:46:43.840 --> 00:46:51.919
It doesn't matter if you can fine tune it to make it 2%, 3%, 4% more faithful to the data.

00:46:51.919 --> 00:46:56.159
It doesn't even matter, I think, as much as it doesn't matter as much as we think it does

00:46:57.120 --> 00:47:04.159
about optimizing tiny little things about how people understand uncertainty or ranges or

00:47:04.159 --> 00:47:08.879
confidence into us, for example. The key thing is that you focus on getting across that core

00:47:08.879 --> 00:47:15.600
message and getting it across accessibly. And finally, we should all be aware that we have

00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:20.399
this incredibly powerful tool in animation, and there are plenty of charts where we would

00:47:20.399 --> 00:47:25.439
unthinkingly just produce a static chart, but an animation can have that much more, I would say,

00:47:25.439 --> 00:47:31.760
in fact, orders of magnitude more impact. And I'm going to end with a call to action in terms of

00:47:31.760 --> 00:47:36.560
things that I would like us as the data viz community to do differently or do more or even

00:47:36.560 --> 00:47:43.679
do for the first time as we go away from this. Which is that first of all, as I mentioned at

00:47:43.679 --> 00:47:49.760
the very start, there's a huge amount of resources out there on how to achieve particular technical

00:47:49.760 --> 00:47:55.439
or visual effects in a chart, but there's not very much on the general way of framing your work

00:47:55.439 --> 00:47:59.840
and the language you use around it in order to achieve the clearest possible communication of a

00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:04.719
message. So what I'd love to see and what I hope to participate in myself is putting out more

00:48:04.719 --> 00:48:12.399
resources that can help people think of and refine this idea of data viz as communication more than

00:48:12.399 --> 00:48:19.439
data viz just as a technical exercise of creating the most objectively good chart possible.

00:48:20.320 --> 00:48:26.000
And secondly, I'd like us to think about accessibility in the broadest of senses when

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:31.600
we make our charts. Because we love making charts and because we know other people,

00:48:32.479 --> 00:48:40.080
most people on this call, I'm sure, on this session, love looking at charts, it can be very

00:48:40.080 --> 00:48:46.080
easy to get into the trap of thinking, oh, what's the coolest thing I can do here that other chart

00:48:46.080 --> 00:48:52.879
people will love? How can I push the envelope? How can I make this chart, you know, especially

00:48:52.879 --> 00:49:00.399
exciting and impressive to people who like charts? But that is the tiniest tip of the iceberg,

00:49:00.399 --> 00:49:06.159
and the rest of this enormous thing beneath the surface of the sea is non-chart people. It's people

00:49:06.159 --> 00:49:11.040
who last looked at charts when they were aged 16, 17, and 18 and then got the hell away from them.

00:49:11.040 --> 00:49:16.560
They're probably people who try to even avoid spreadsheets. But that is an enormous audience

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:21.840
of people who could love charts if they just had charts that spoke to them and charts that didn't

00:49:21.840 --> 00:49:25.840
try to be too smart, charts that didn't condescend to them. So the other thing I'd

00:49:25.840 --> 00:49:31.199
love us all to do is think more about making charts, not that are graphics for graphics editors,

00:49:31.199 --> 00:49:38.000
as someone once said to me, but charts that are for your mum, your dad, and, you know, everyone

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:43.760
else out there in the world. So thank you very much for bearing with me through all of this, and

00:49:44.399 --> 00:49:49.199
please do fire me all your questions. And I'd also encourage you in the spirit of what I've

00:49:49.199 --> 00:49:53.520
been saying here, do send me a tweet or an email or anything like that with other questions you

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:57.040
have if we don't get time for them just now, because I'd love to hear your thoughts on all

00:49:57.040 --> 00:50:07.360
of this stuff.

